&gt; configura
&gt; tion options), I could create any number of subclasses representing
&gt; specifi
&gt; c combinations of configuration settings that I want to test.
&gt; 
&gt; Does this seem right? I mean, is this an appropriate use of inherritance?
&gt; 
&gt; Thanks for any advice you can provide.

Personally I&#39;d go for the simplest solution, in your case having two
subclasses performing the test with the two configurations.

Generalizing the problem introduces something like a parameterized testcase
and parameterized test suite. I implemented those two classes on top of JUnit
a while ago and never felt the need to use it since. I offer to upload the
sources if anyone is interested. JUnit must be slightly patched for them to
work, though.

I have an inkling that the reason for me not using parameterized test cases
lies somewhere in the implications of doing test first design with a strong
focus on separating concerns and testing in isolation. Thereby configuration
dependent behaviour usually resides in one or more strategy objects and is
tested there. The configuration variations I want to have when testing the
service object itself are so few that I do it directly in the testXXXX()-methods.

Johannes
