&lt;BODY bgColor=#ffffff&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;Hi,&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;I would like some advice on how to organize tests. 
I seem to find myself facing many instances of the following 
pattern:&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;I have some sort of service I would like to test. I 
would like to test a variety of features of the service: we could call them A, 
B, C, D and E. Now the service can be configured to operate in various 
modes.&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;For example, I have a service involving messaging 
using TCP/IP connections. It can run using either plain, raw TCP connections, or 
alternatively it should work with SSL as well. Virtually all of the code doesn&#39;t 
care which mode it is in (in other words, this distinction is transparent to my 
code). So of course I simply want to write one set of tests to verify the 
correct operation of features A, B, C, D and E.&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;It&#39;s even tempting not to bother with running all 
the tests using both modes. But to be thorough I want to do so.&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;Now an organization that seems natural to me is 
something like this:&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;class TcpTests extends TestCase {&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; public void setUp() throws 
Exception {&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial 
size=2&gt;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;tcpService = new 
TcpService();&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; boolean 
useSSL = something;&nbsp; // ??&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 
tcpService.setUseSSL(useSSL);&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 
tcpService.start();&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; }&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; public void testA() throws 
Exception { ... }&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; public void testB() throws 
Exception { ... }&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; ....&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; public void testE() throws 
Exception { ... }&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; public void tearDown() throws 
Exception {&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 
tcpService.stop();&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; }&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;}&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;How do I run this set of tests in both modes (first 
with plain connections, say, and then with SSL connections)?&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;Is my problem that I have put the wrong sort of 
thing in the setUp() method?&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;Another way that came to mind was to ignore the 
setUp() and tearDown() routines, and do something like the 
following:&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;class TcpTests extends TestCase {&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; public void testWithoutSSL() 
{&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 
initTcp(false);&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 
doASeries();&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; }&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; public void testWithSSL() 
{&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 
initTcp(true);&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 
doASeries();&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; }&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; private void initTcp(boolean 
useSSL) {&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; // as in 
setUp() of first example&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; }&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; private void doASeries() 
{&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 
doFeatureA();&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 
doFeatureB();&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 
..&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 
doFeatureE();&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; }&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;}&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;Besides being somehow aesthetically not pleasing, 
this means that from JUnit&#39;s point of view I have only two tests. I feel I 
should have ten. I guess, also, that if a particular feature fails, then all the 
other features that were to be tested after it will not even get tried. That&#39;s 
obviously not right.&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;Then the other thing I thought was, would this be 
an appropriate occasion to use a hierarchy of TestCase classes? In other words, 
maybe I go back to the first pattern (above), but make it an abstract class. 
Define an abstract method, called perhaps something like getSSLSetting(). Have 
setUp() call this method to determine what the setting should be. Now I create 
two (concrete) subclasses, one for each possible setting of the useSSL flag that 
I want to test. In the subclasses, the only method I have to define is 
getSSLSetting(). JUnit sees two different TestCase classes (I have to put two 
different classes into my TestSuite: the concrete classes only, of course, not 
the abstract super-class.) Each of the two has 5 tests, for a total of 
10.&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;I guess, generalizing this (assuming I have a more 
complex set of configuration options), I could create any number of subclasses 
representing specific combinations of configuration settings that I want to 
test.&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;Does this seem right? I mean, is this an 
appropriate use of inherritance?&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;Thanks for any advice you can provide.&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;&lt;/FONT&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;FONT face=Arial size=2&gt;&nbsp;- Alan Bram&lt;/FONT&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;
